## System level commands

- uname
-> uname is used to display information about the operating system currently in use.

- uptime
-> It is used to display how long the system has been running.

- whoami
-> It is used to display the currently logged-in-user.

- who
->  It is used to display users who are currently logged in to the system.

- which
-> It is used to display the full path of the command that is available in the system.

- ID
-> It used to display the user ID (UID) and group ID (GID) if the cureent user.

- sudo
-> sudo allows a permitted user to run a command as a superuser (root).

- shutdown
-> shutdown is used to power off the system in a safe manner.

- reboot
-> reboot is used to restart the system in a safe manner.

- apt (advanced package tool)
-> It is used to install, update, and remove packages in the system.
-> linux has different application 
 Examples: yum , dnf ,pacman ,portage.

## User & Group Management

- useradd
-> useradd is used to create a new user and its home directory in the system.

- passwd
-> It is used  to set,change or update a user password in the system.

- su
-> It is used to switch the current user to  another user in the system.

- groupadd
-> groupadd is used to create a new group in the system.

## File permission command

- chmod
-> chmod is used to change the permissions of files and directories.

- umask
-> umask defines the default permission mode for newly created files and directories.

- chown
-> chown is used to change the user and/or group ownership of files and directories.

- chgrp
-> chgrp is used to change the group ownership of files and directories.

## compression command

- zip
-> zip is used to compress the files and directories into a zip archive.

- unzip
->  unzip is used to decompress and extract files from a zip archive.

-  gunzip
-> gunzip is used to decompress gzip-compressed files and restore them to their original form.

## Networking & Transfer
- scp (secure copy protocol)
-> scp is used to transfer files and directories securely over a network using SSH.
Examples: 
Local → Remote
    scp file.txt user@server:/home/user/
Remote → Local
    scp user@server:/home/user/file.txt  .


- rsync
-> rsync is used to efficiently copy and synchronize files and directories between systems or directories.
Examples: 
Local → Local
 rsync -av source/ destination/
Local → Remote
 rsync -av source/ user@server:/home/user/
Remote → Local
 rsync -av user@server:/home/user/source/ .
